<doc id="20790" wikidata="Q3311767" url="?curid=20790" title="Mary, mother of John Mark">
<text>Mary, mother of [[John Mark]] – commonly associated with Mark the Evangelist – is mentioned in the New Testament of the Christian Bible, in Acts 12:12, where it is said that, after his escape from prison, Peter went to her house: &quot;When he realized this, he went to the house of Mary, the mother of John whose other name was Mark, where many were gathered together and were praying.&quot; This seems to be the only mention of her in the Bible. From this it would appear that Mary&#x27;s house was a place of gathering for the Apostles and other Christians. 

The Monastery of Saint Mark, in the Old City of Jerusalem, contains a 6th-century inscription claiming the place is the site of &quot;the house of Mary, mother of John Mark&quot;. 

==See also==
*&quot;Easton&#x27;s Bible Dictionary&quot;, 1897

